\begin_layout Subsection
Shutdown and Exit
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When optimal profit is negative (market price is low) - should the firm
 shutdown/exit? In the long run - 
\series bold
yes
\series default
 (no fixed costs, only variable ones).
 In the short run - 
\series bold
maybe
\series default
 (still paying fixed costs, can make things worse).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Fifxed costs are 
\series bold
crucial
\series default
 for understanding how a business works and makes its decisions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In some cases one would prefer to open and have the business running, despist
 anticipation of losses.
 Keeping it open, the profit is: 
\begin_inset Formula $P\cdot X-FC-VC$
\end_inset

, but when it's shut down it's 
\begin_inset Formula $-FC$
\end_inset

, thus if 
\begin_inset Formula $P\cdot X-VC>0$
\end_inset

, the business should be kept open.
\end_layout

