\begin_layout Section
Competitive Markets
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The combination of the previous two theories discussed (consumer's theory
 & firm's theory) leads us to the market definition.
 In competitive market, each buyer & seller is a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

price taker
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, decisions are made only on how much to buy / sell.
 There are other market types, for simplificaiton we only consider competitive
 market with a single available good here.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Market demand / supply is the sum of quantities demanded / supplies by all
 consumers / firms at each market price.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The short-run equilibrium combines supply & demand (might differ from the
 long-run - because of the number of operating firms).
 It is defined as the price, at which demand equals supply.
 A higher price leads to a surplus, a lower one - to a shortage.
 Eventually the equilibrium will be reached.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Example: housing prices in Israel.
 There is a similar rise in rent prices (at least, in the long-term).
 There are many arguments on why it happens, and many efforts to lower it,
 but at the end there is a very simple observation: the number of people
 added each year to the demand side is substantially and systematically
 higher than the supply side (new apartments), which leads to a shortage
 (on average ~20 thousand per year).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Comparative Statics (D Shifters)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Deals with the question: what can change the equilibrium? If the demand
 curve shifts, a new eqilibrium is established
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For example, consider an increase in gasoline price leads to increase of
 hybrid cars demand, as it is a substitute, thus some customers are 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

redirected
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 to it as an alternative.
 The demand shift induced movement along the supply curve.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Comparative Statics (S Shifters)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the supply curve shifts, a new equilibrium is established.
 For example, when many additional hybrid cars sellers enter the market,
 the supply curve shifts right, and there is movement along the demand curve.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Long-run equilibrium
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the long-run, firms are free to enter/exit the market (no fixed cost
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

barrier
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 anymore).
 We use 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

exit
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 for long-run and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

shutdown
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 for the short-run.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus, their number is not 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

given
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (exogenous), but is an endogeous variable: positive (negative) profit leads
 to new firms enter (some firms leave), supply shifts right (left), price
 falls (rises) and profit falls (rises).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The entry/exit process is complete, when firms earn zeo (economic) profit
 (alternative accounting profit).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the long-run, 
\series bold
you can never outdo the alternative
\series default
 you have.
 Zero profit implies: 
\series bold
price = average cost
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In an equilibrium, MC equals AC.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the short run, the equilibrium is only defined by 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 (units number) and 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 (price).
 In the long it's also 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 (firms number) and 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 (units produced by each firm).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Notice that accounting profit = revenue - explicit cost.
 Economic profit = revenue - explicit cost - implicit cost.
 When the economic profit is 0, it means that accounting profit equals the
 implicit cost.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Welfare Economics
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An outcome of a market is, basically, allocation of resources: who produces
 / consumes and how much.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Instead of asking what is the outcome and how do we reach it, we ask: is
 that a good result? Can we do better?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Consumer surplus
\series default
 measures 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

how better off
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 are consumers as a result of consuming the product.
 It equals to benefit, minus the price.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Producer surplus
\series default
 measures the wellbeing of sellers: the price they charged, minus the producing
 cost.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Total surplus
\series default
 is the sum of producers' & consumers' surpluses.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Different market structures result in different allocations, thus, different
 levels of surplus.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Which market outcome maximizes everyone's surplus (efficiency)? - 
\series bold
First Welfare Theorem: Perfectly competitive markets lead to the highest
 possible surplus.
\end_layout

